{
  "id": "019d31e5-8c4a-7822-84db-a0d104912ac1",
  "content": "# Decision: Redb VECTORS Table Over Custom Binary Sidecar (2026-03-27)\n\n## Decision\nStore embedding vectors in a dedicated Redb table with raw f32 bytes, not a custom binary sidecar file. Strip embeddings from JSON knowledge files.\n\n## Why\n- Custom sidecar requires ~500-1000 lines for crash safety, concurrency, compaction, alignment, mmap lifecycle\n- Redb provides ACID transactions, MVCC, crash recovery out of the box — already a dependency\n- Performance gap is negligible: Redb VECTORS rebuild ~0.3-0.5s vs sidecar ~0.1-0.2s at 100K entries\n- 5-persona review identified 7 blocking issues with sidecar approach; Redb eliminates all of them\n- Redb ENTRIES table already stores embeddings (as JSON bytes) — the data is already there\n\n## How to Apply\n- Add `VECTORS` Redb table: key = UUID bytes [u8; 16], value = raw f32 bytes [u8; 3072]\n- Write vectors to VECTORS table inside existing `index_entry_into` write transaction\n- Rebuild reads from VECTORS table via `bytemuck::cast_slice`, not JSON files\n- Strip embeddings from JSON via `#[serde(skip_serializing)]` on `embedding` field\n- Migration: two-phase — populate VECTORS table first, then strip JSON files\n- Preserve old embedding-in-JSON read path for one major version (backward compat)\n\n## Supersedes\nPrevious design from 2026-03-19 (`decisions/2026-03-19-json-embedding-exclusion-design.md`) proposed simply excluding embeddings from JSON with HNSW+Redb as cache. This decision adds the dedicated VECTORS table for optimal rebuild performance.",
  "source_version": "chore/dev-loop-knowledge-persistence",
  "scope_id": "corvia",
  "workstream": "main",
